David Packer (davep@paladin.corp.sgi.com) wrote:

: Hey Dan,

: I think we've talked before:

: In article <FAIGIN.94Apr8092012@solarium.aero.org>, faigin@aero.org writes:
: > Most computers are virus proof; it's just PCs that are not. PCs, or I should
: > say MS-DOS systems, have the property that the operating system is in the same
: > domain as applications; thus applications can muck with the operating system.
: > 
: > In most other systems (for example, most Unixii), the operating system runs in
: > a different mode, and application programs cannot tamper with the operating
: > systems. This is one of the characteristics of a Reference Validation
: > Monitor--that it is tamperproof. Anything with this characteristic should be
: > immune from viruses that attack the operating system.
: >

: I think one thing to note, is that even though Unix systems are more difficult
: to "muck" with the kernel. Who says that the kernel needs to be mucked
: for a virus to take effect?? Any root ran process has full system access
: therefore allowing the ability of viruses to be implemented. 

: From my experience with UNIX almost every manufacturer (except SGI, of course)
							 ^^^^^^^^^^^
Except for that unique little "feature" in SGI Irix that allows one
to read any user's mail files.

: of UNIX boxes has blatant over-looked security holes. In a non-trusted
: environment a smart hack could figure ways to make a virus spreadable
: through a net. You want to really frusturate a work group, nail the NIS
: server.

: Dave Packer
: Silicon Graphics Inc.


: BTW,

: I personally don't think there is such thing as a Virus-proof computer,
: unless of course it's turned off.

